This project focuses on the manipulation and analysis of a dataset about airports, using the Python library called Pandas. The project involves a number of tasks including loading the data set as a data frame, removing unnecessary columns, identifying and handling null values, and grouping and analyzing the data.

The database has been extracted from the following website https://openflights.org/data.html.

In [91]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

- Loading of the dataset as a dataframe.¶

With the pandas read_csv method we can load and read files with that extension. Since the given file does not contain a header we will have to clarify it with the header=None method. We are also going to clarify with the encoding='utf-8' method so that there are no symbology conflicts. In the second line of code with the .columns method we are going to create the header.

In [92]:
df_airports = pd.read_csv('airports_extended.csv',header = None,  encoding='utf-8')
df_airports.columns = ['AirportID','Name','City','Country','IATA','ICAO','Latitude','Longitude','Altitude','Timezone','DST','Tz','Type','Source']

- In the statistical summary above it seems that in column TZ there is a rare value \N, check the proportion of them with value_counts.¶

To get the percentage of '\N' inside the TZ column we first create a variable containing all the values of TZ with the value_counts method. Then we use the method .loc[] to locate '\N'. Finally we divide it by the len of the TZ column.

In [98]:
value_counts = df_airports_v1['Tz'].value_counts()
value_countsare_values = value_counts.loc['\\N']
proportion = value_countsare_values / len(df_airports_v1['Tz'])
print(f'The percentage of "/N" in the Tz column is: {proportion.round(2)} %')

The percentage of "/N" in the Tz column is: 0.34 %

- Reload the dataset so that null values are correctly interpreted (repeat section 4, delete columns).¶

Now that we know how many '\N' values we have what we are going to do is to reload the Df and repeat the previous steps. When we have completed we proceed to change the '\N' values to NaN values with the replace method and numpy's np.nan function.

In [99]:
df_airports_v3 = pd.read_csv('airports_extended.csv', header= None, encoding='utf-8')
df_airports_v3.columns = ['AirportID','Name','City','Country','IATA','ICAO','Latitude','Longitude','Altitude','Timezone','DST','Tz','Type','Source']
df_airports_v3.drop(['AirportID','Latitude','Longitude','Altitude'], axis = 1,inplace=True)
df_airports_v3['Tz'].replace('\\N', np.nan, inplace=True)
df_airports_v3['IATA'].replace('\\N', np.nan, inplace=True)
df_airports_v3['ICAO'].replace('\\N', np.nan, inplace=True)
df_airports_v3['Timezone'].replace('\\N', np.nan, inplace=True)
df_airports_v3['Type'].replace('\\N', np.nan, inplace=True)
df_airports_v3['Source'].replace('\\N', np.nan, inplace=True)
df_airports_v3['DST'].replace('\\N', np.nan, inplace=True)

Thinking about a context for the airport database, I thought it would be interesting to know if there is a relationship between the number of airports and the number of inhabitants in different countries. I started searching on the web and found a database with information about countries. By means of a merge I joined the two tables and I was able to extract the useful information. By means of graphs I am going to show the number of airports per inhabitants and the number of inhabitants per airport. All this using the top 10 countries with the highest number of inhabitants worldwide.

- Load the original DF of Airports¶

We can see in the above graph that there is no direct relationship between the number of inhabitants and the number of airports. Since China is the most populated country in our list and has less airports than the USA, which is located in the number 3 position of the most populated countries. In conclusion, there is no relationship whatsoever.

- Conclusions¶

With this analysis I'am reach the conclusion that there is no relation between the number of inhabitants and the number of countries. Maybe there is a relation with the income per person, tourist zones or international connections. Due to the lack of databases and information I have not been able to draw that conclusion, I have been searching the internet for different types of databases with extra information but I have not been able to find the correct one.
